33 A BILL
34 TO BE ENTITLED
35 AN ACT
36
37 Relating to public K-12 education; to create the Home
38 Schooling Opportunities for Military Education (HOME) Act; to
39 define "covered military service"; to require active duty
40 military parents performing covered military service to
41 provide notice of an intention to home school dependent
42 children and to comply with state law relating to home
43 schooling; to allow home school students of active duty
44 military parents performing covered military service to use
45 public school facilities and equipment under certain
46 circumstances; to require local school systems to provide home
47 school students with disabilities of active duty military
48 parents performing covered military service access to special
49 education services; and to amend Section 16-1-52.1, Code of
50 Alabama 1975, to require local school systems to allow home
51 school and other students of active duty military parents
52 performing covered military service to participate in
53 interscholastic sports provided in the local school system.
54 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
55 Section 1. This act shall be known and may be cited as
56 the Home Schooling Opportunities for Military Education (HOME)
Page 2

the Home Schooling Opportunities for Military Education (HOME)
SB191 INTRODUCED
57 Act.
58 Section 2. (a) For the purposes of this section, the
59 following terms have the following meanings:
60 (1) BONA FIDE CHANGE IN DUTY STATION OR RESIDENCE. A
61 required relocation pursuant to military orders, whether
62 temporary or permanent, that necessitates that the service
63 member obtain lodging outside the normal commuting area of the
64 member's principal residence.
65 (2) COVERED MILITARY SERVICE. Active duty military
66 service by a member of the Armed Forces of the United States,
67 including a member of the reserve components or the Alabama
68 National Guard, who is:
69 a. Serving on active duty under federal authority; or
70 b. Serving on active duty under state authority
71 pursuant to an order of the Governor or other lawful state
72 authority, when the service requires a bona fide change in
73 duty station or residence.
74 (b) Any parent who is a member of the Armed Forces of
75 the United States and performing covered military service who
76 moves into a new school system and begins home instruction
77 after the school year has begun, shall notify as soon as
78 practicable the local superintendent of education of his or
79 her intention to home school his or her dependent child and,
80 within 30 days after providing notice, shall comply with all
81 state requirements for home schooling. The local
82 superintendent of education may require the parent to provide
83 a copy of his or her permanent change of station orders to
84 substantiate the move.
Page 3

substantiate the move.
SB191 INTRODUCED
85 (c) A student who is the dependent of a member of the
86 Armed Forces of the United States performing covered military
87 service and is home schooled may use public school facilities
88 and equipment on the same basis as regularly enrolled students
89 if all of the following conditions are satisfied:
90 (1) The use does not disrupt regular school activities.
91 (2) The use is approved by the school principal in
92 accordance with local board of education policy.
93 (3) The use does not create any additional expense for
94 the school.
95 (4) The use is directly related to the academic program
96 of the student.
97 (5) The use of potentially hazardous areas including,
98 but not limited to, shops, laboratories, and the gymnasium, is
99 supervised by a designated employee of the school
100 administrative staff.
101 (d) A local school system shall provide a genuine
102 opportunity for home school students with disabilities, who
103 are the dependents of a member of the Armed Forces of the
104 United States performing covered military service, to access
105 special education and related services from the school system
106 within which they reside. This subsection shall not be
107 construed as conferring the procedural protections and rights
108 under Part B of the Individuals with Disabilities Education
109 Act (IDEA) to those students and their parents or guardians.
110 The State Board of Education shall adopt rules as necessary to
111 implement this subsection.
112 Section 3. Section 16-1-52.1 of the Code of Alabama
